chance to do justice to in the book.

00:04:31.450 --> 00:04:40.940
And the Arbeely family are one of
the most important of those groups.

00:04:40.940 --> 00:04:44.940
They are indeed the first
Syrian immigrant family

00:04:44.940 --> 00:04:46.950
to come to the United States.

00:04:46.950 --> 00:04:50.120
They called themselves the
first Syrian immigrant family,

00:04:50.120 --> 00:04:53.470
but people always try to
say that they are maybe not,

00:04:53.470 --> 00:04:56.440
maybe there were other Syrians
before them, but indeed they were,

00:04:56.440 --> 00:05:01.930
in fact, the first Syrian family
to come to the United States.

00:05:01.930 --> 00:05:07.580 position:56%
And the story of the Joseph Arbeely
family tells us how they constructed

00:05:07.580 --> 00:05:12.450
an Arab-American identity, in fact,
the first Arab-American identity

00:05:12.450 --> 00:05:13.870
of course in the United States,

00:05:13.870 --> 00:05:16.740
since they were the
first Syrian family.

00:05:16.740 --> 00:05:21.600
They constructed a double
identity and that looked both east

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:25.390
and west [inaudible]
like and keeping both

00:05:25.390 --> 00:05:30.870
of those identities separate, but
- and mesmerizing their audiences,

00:05:30.870 --> 00:05:34.070
both in life and on the stage.

00:05:34.070 --> 00:05:39.510
They were both Oriental and
American at the same time.

00:05:39.510 --> 00:05:42.400
I want to say.

00:05:42.400 --> 00:05:45.970
first before I begin, that these
photographs have never been seen

00:05:45.970 --> 00:05:50.770
by anyone in the world before, so
you'll all have a special treat.

00:05:50.770 --> 00:05:53.490
The performance photographs are

00:05:53.490 --> 00:05:55.590
from the National Anthropological
Archives

00:05:55.590 --> 00:06:00.510
of the Smithsonian Institution
hidden deep away in the archives

00:06:00.510 --> 00:06:05.140
and the family photographs are
from a collateral descendant

00:06:05.140 --> 00:06:11.570
of the Arbeelys' who found me on
Facebook and who live in Texas now.

00:06:11.570 --> 00:06:15.860
Habeeb Arbeely and his
daughter Dania Arbeely.

00:06:15.860 --> 00:06:26.460
Okay. Yosef Aweth Hannah Alcolush
[sp] was born in the village

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:36.370 position:56%
of Erbil about five miles outside of
Damascus in 1828 and he was educated

00:06:36.370 --> 00:06:40.350
at the Damascus Orthodox College
and became a teacher there,

00:06:40.350 --> 00:06:45.430
married in Damascus, had his
first three children in Damascus.

00:06:45.430 --> 00:06:52.420 position:56%
In 1860 he moved his family of three
children and his wife to Beirut.

00:06:52.420 --> 00:06:56.650
Some say it was because of the
sectarian violence that was going

00:06:56.650 --> 00:07:01.060
on in Syria, in Greater
Syria at that time.

00:07:01.060 --> 00:07:04.230
Some say it was because he
saw opportunities in Beirut

00:07:04.230 --> 00:07:06.880
that he had not had in Damascus.

00:07:06.880 --> 00:07:13.070
In any case he took his children
to Beirut in 1860, set up a school

00:07:13.070 --> 00:07:18.690
for the exiles of Orthodox
Damascenes there,

00:07:18.690 --> 00:07:22.710
and was said to have collaborated
with Cornelius Van Dyck,

00:07:22.710 --> 00:07:26.090
one of the founders of the Syrian
Protestant College in Beirut

00:07:26.090 --> 00:07:28.480
to translate the Bible into Arabic.

00:07:28.480 --> 00:07:33.810
So he had contact very early
on with American missionaries

00:07:33.810 --> 00:07:37.110
and the Syrian Protestant College.

00:07:37.110 --> 00:07:42.320
His oldest son Abraham, who's on
the left standing up in the left

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:46.520
of the picture took a medical
degree at Syrian Protestant College

00:07:46.520 --> 00:07:50.590
in 1872, and then went on to
get a second medical degree

00:07:50.590 --> 00:07:51.950
in Constantinople.

00:07:51.950 --> 00:07:59.420
Later his third son, Felala,
also in the picture standing

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:06.640
up on the second from the
right, took a BA at SPC in 1872

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:10.280
and then a medical degree in 1876.

00:08:10.280 --> 00:08:16.420
In 1878 Yosef decided that his
family was coming to America.

00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:20.430
No one from Syria that he knew
or anyone knew had ever been

00:08:20.430 --> 00:08:22.690
to America before,
no Syrian that is.

00:08:22.690 --> 00:08:26.680
But he must have become enamored
of the country or learned

00:08:26.680 --> 00:08:30.610
about the opportunities or thought
he saw an opportunity in America.

00:08:30.610 --> 00:08:35.720
They set sail from
Beirut in July of 1878,

00:08:35.720 --> 00:08:40.500
stopped off at the Universal
Exposition in Paris on the way,

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:43.880
and they became great
goers to fairs.

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:46.300
They went to every fair that
they could possibly go to.

00:08:46.300 --> 00:08:47.890
They loved these world fairs.

00:08:47.890 --> 00:08:51.810 position:56%
World's Fairs the first one they
went to was in Paris and they landed

00:08:51.810 --> 00:08:56.680
in New York on August 21st in 1878.

00:08:56.680 --> 00:09:02.710
This is a photograph of them in
Beirut just before they set sail.

00:09:02.710 --> 00:09:06.950
It's the only known photograph of
Mary, the wife, who's sitting next

00:09:06.950 --> 00:09:10.520
to Yosef the father
obviously in the front.

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:13.840
And you will notice that the two
young boys are holding books.

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:17.730
This was a trope that was used
in the Middle East often to show

00:09:17.730 --> 00:09:21.280 position:56%
that they were literate, and the
whole family of course was literate,

00:09:21.280 --> 00:09:23.940
even the young boys at that time.

00:09:23.940 --> 00:09:32.230
The back of the photograph has
Najeeb's handwriting on the back.

00:09:32.230 --> 00:09:36.710
The Smithsonian is not entirely
sure where this came from,

00:09:36.710 --> 00:09:41.560
but I think it was actually given
to, probably not the president

00:09:41.560 --> 00:09:45.300 position:56%
of the United States himself, but
one of his staff members when Najeeb

00:09:45.300 --> 00:09:49.640
and his father visited
the White House in 1881.

00:09:49.640 --> 00:09:53.530
But the picture was taken
earlier before they'd -

00:09:53.530 --> 00:09:55.610
before they left Beirut.

00:09:55.610 --> 00:09:57.280
When the day they landed,

00:09:57.280 --> 00:10:02.040 position:56%
the Arbeelys' impressed the New
York newspaper reporters like crazy.

00:10:02.040 --> 00:10:04.490
They were literate.

00:10:04.490 --> 00:10:08.430
They were fluent in English,
at least some of them were.

00:10:08.430 --> 00:10:12.750
They clearly understood what they
were about and the newspapers wrote

00:10:12.750 --> 00:10:15.770
about them as the first
Syrian immigrant family,

00:10:15.770 --> 00:10:18.820
which is what the family
said about themselves.

00:10:18.820 --> 00:10:22.890
"We are the first and
we're here to pave the way

00:10:22.890 --> 00:10:26.270
for other Syrians to come."

00:10:27.310 --> 00:10:30.020
He came without a job, apparently.

00:10:30.020 --> 00:10:33.370
And so after a few days the
newspapers started to think

00:10:33.370 --> 00:10:36.720
"Oh maybe he's - they're
going to all become a burden

00:10:36.720 --> 00:10:38.380
on the city of New York."

00:10:38.380 --> 00:10:40.960
Because they're indigent,
they have no money.

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:45.480
A few days after that they decided
that they were secretly rich

00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:48.200
and that they had a bank
account in New Jersey.

00:10:48.200 --> 00:10:50.320
How they could have set up
a bank account in New Jersey

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:54.490
when they had arrived three
days before is a little bit odd,

00:10:54.490 --> 00:10:56.600
but they thought he had a
bank account in New Jersey

00:10:56.600 --> 00:10:59.440
and that he was pretending
to be poor in order

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:01.540
to get the American government

00:11:01.540 --> 00:11:05.140
or the New York government
to help them.

00:11:05.140 --> 00:11:10.290
In fact, it shows to me
the kind of schizophrenia

00:11:10.290 --> 00:11:14.220
of Americans toward Syrians,
which began that first week,

00:11:14.220 --> 00:11:17.360
because they didn't know
whether they were wonderful,

00:11:17.360 --> 00:11:20.760
ready to be assimilated
entrepreneurs

00:11:20.760 --> 00:11:25.010
or whether they were
liars, cheats and beggars.

00:11:25.010 --> 00:11:28.320
And both the Arbeelys'
were subjected to both.

00:11:28.320 --> 00:11:34.280
In any case, he was offered a job
at the Presbyterian College in,

00:11:34.280 --> 00:11:39.570
wait for this, Maryville Tennessee,
which he accepted may have been

00:11:39.570 --> 00:11:41.440
through his contacts in Beirut.

00:11:41.440 --> 00:11:44.890
They all got on the train
and went to Tennessee.

00:11:44.890 --> 00:11:48.970
They were a family of nine,
because they arrived in New York

00:11:48.970 --> 00:11:55.250
with the six sons, the
parents, and a niece, Jimelee.

00:11:55.250 --> 00:12:00.080
And they arrived in Maryville,
Tennessee, nine of them

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:03.530
and the Maryville, Tennessee
had a population of 1100.

00:12:03.530 --> 00:12:05.950
So you can imagine
how they stood out,

00:12:05.950 --> 00:12:10.750
particularly if they were dressed
as they were in the Beirut picture,

00:12:10.750 --> 00:12:12.810
but by the time they got

00:12:12.810 --> 00:12:17.300
to Maryville they were
already - they settled in.

00:12:17.300 --> 00:12:21.510 position:56%
The newspapers treated them as if
they were normal Maryville residents

00:12:21.510 --> 00:12:26.750
and the two sons opened
their medical practices,

00:12:26.750 --> 00:12:28.880
Felala and Abraham.

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:32.470
They were immediately
accepted as doctors

00:12:32.470 --> 00:12:36.040
by the Tennessee population,
as just regular doctors.

00:12:36.040 --> 00:12:41.570
Clearly the Syrian Protestant
College diploma was all they needed

00:12:41.570 --> 00:12:45.820 position:56%
to set up shop and Felala, in
particular who practice in Maryville

00:12:45.820 --> 00:12:49.610
for quite a few years would be
mentioned along with other doctors

00:12:49.610 --> 00:12:53.070
as if he were just one
of the Tennessee doctors.

00:12:53.070 --> 00:12:55.660
Nothing. They talked about
their comings and goings,

00:12:55.660 --> 00:12:58.640
but only in the context of other
people's comings and goings.

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:02.040
They went to Knoxville and spent
the night at such and such a hotel.

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:06.790
Every once in a while they
would say something like

00:13:06.790 --> 00:13:09.430
"They're an industrious family."

00:13:09.430 --> 00:13:10.820
Or "Very sober."

00:13:10.820 --> 00:13:13.440
Or "Very, very good workers."

00:13:13.440 --> 00:13:16.180
And they would never say
that about a Tennesseean.

00:13:16.180 --> 00:13:17.480
It goes without saying.

00:13:17.480 --> 00:13:20.170
So of course they were
seen as different,

00:13:20.170 --> 00:13:23.870
but in mainly a positive way.

00:13:23.870 --> 00:13:28.720
Joseph's wife, Mary, whom you
see in this picture sitting next

00:13:28.720 --> 00:13:32.080
to him died in 1880,
only two years -

00:13:32.080 --> 00:13:33.840
less than two years
after they arrived.

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:37.780
She's buried in Maryville,
in the Maryville cemetery.

00:13:37.780 --> 00:13:40.280
And she's the only one of
the family, oddly enough,

00:13:40.280 --> 00:13:41.820
who has a stone erected to her.

00:13:41.820 --> 00:13:45.760 position:56%
Her children carved a stone for her.

00:13:45.760 --> 00:13:52.360
And soon after her death the family
started their peripatetic life.

00:13:52.360 --> 00:13:57.980
First, Yosef and his oldest son,
Abraham, went to Texas looking

00:13:57.980 --> 00:14:02.950
for a place to establish a
Syrian colony, which they did all

00:14:02.950 --> 00:14:05.490
of their lives and they
never found the place -

00:14:05.490 --> 00:14:07.000
a place that suited them.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:13.460
Abraham hung up his medical
shingle in San Antonio, Texas.

00:14:13.460 --> 00:14:15.840
Yosef came back to Maryville.

00:14:15.840 --> 00:14:19.360
His three youngest sons went
to Maryville High School,

00:14:19.360 --> 00:14:22.080
which was part of the
College and then went

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:26.880
to a Quaker School 300
miles from home for college.

00:14:26.880 --> 00:14:33.600 position:56%
And Najeeb, the third youngest went
to law school at Marysville College.

00:14:33.600 --> 00:14:35.620
At the same time that
they were doing all

00:14:35.620 --> 00:14:39.130
of this educational stuff
they started to travel

00:14:39.130 --> 00:14:42.610
around first Eastern
Tennessee, then the east coast

00:14:42.610 --> 00:14:46.400
and then the whole
country doing shows.

00:14:47.930 --> 00:14:54.160 position:56%
This is them again in Tennessee
taken right after the death of Mary.

00:14:54.160 --> 00:14:56.030 position:56%
This is what the empty chair is for.

00:14:56.030 --> 00:14:58.070
It's a memorial to her.

00:14:58.070 --> 00:15:01.170
And Jimelee, the niece
is on the left.

00:15:01.170 --> 00:15:05.850
And I just want to show you
this comparative picture,

00:15:05.850 --> 00:15:09.470
because the picture on the right
is the only picture that's ever

00:15:09.470 --> 00:15:14.230
circulated of the family and it's
been reproduced in many things,

00:15:14.230 --> 00:15:18.740
including a [inaudible] book on
this - on Syrian immigration.

00:15:18.740 --> 00:15:25.070
And this sign says "I and my
family are enjoying freedom here."

00:15:25.070 --> 00:15:29.270 position:56%
So it was clearly meant as a
photograph to be sent home to Syria.

00:15:29.270 --> 00:15:31.880
They wanted the Syrians to
follow them and they wanted

00:15:31.880 --> 00:15:34.620
to be the founders of a colony.

00:15:34.620 --> 00:15:40.840
So they began to travel
around giving shows, lectures,

00:15:40.840 --> 00:15:44.370
and entertainments
about the Holy Land.

00:15:44.370 --> 00:15:48.350
Oh I - sorry this is just
the - to show that Najeeb -

00:15:48.350 --> 00:15:52.060
the children were in
American schools.

00:15:52.060 --> 00:15:53.600
So they went - they began to go

00:15:53.600 --> 00:15:57.750
around giving programs
on the Holy Land.

00:15:57.750 --> 00:16:01.040
First Yosef went with
one or two of his sons.

00:16:01.040 --> 00:16:03.830
They would give a lecture
about the Holy Land.

00:16:03.830 --> 00:16:05.690
And the fact that they
were called people

00:16:05.690 --> 00:16:10.740
from the Holy Land made it
acceptable and probably uplifting

00:16:10.740 --> 00:16:14.370
for people to come to this event.

00:16:14.370 --> 00:16:20.330
They charge 25 cents for adults,
15 cents for children under 12,

00:16:20.330 --> 00:16:22.410
and according to many of the review

00:16:22.410 --> 00:16:26.940
that were done afterwards
every place was packed.

00:16:26.940 --> 00:16:29.970
They performed and
