00:32:45.130 --> 00:32:48.710
in the United States saying
"Your honor is worth everything

00:32:48.710 --> 00:32:50.930
and you must maintain your honor."

00:32:50.930 --> 00:32:55.690
And "The almighty dollar is not
what you should be going after."

00:32:55.690 --> 00:32:58.770
Najeeb did many other things
besides run the newspaper.

00:32:58.770 --> 00:33:00.990
He was an interpreter
at Ellis Island,

00:33:00.990 --> 00:33:03.150
a full time interpreter
at Ellis Island.

00:33:03.150 --> 00:33:07.540
He made a $1,000 year doing
that, which was a good salary.

00:33:07.540 --> 00:33:11.850
He also continued to buy
and sell Syrian goods.

00:33:11.850 --> 00:33:14.850
He took out concessions at
every single World's Fair

00:33:14.850 --> 00:33:19.200
and then would rent out
booths to other Syrians.

00:33:19.200 --> 00:33:21.230
He continued to perform.

00:33:21.230 --> 00:33:27.590
There's a marvelous article
in 1894 that he wrote himself

00:33:27.590 --> 00:33:31.690
where he assembled a troop
of 100 Syrians to perform

00:33:31.690 --> 00:33:34.160
for the Shriners in Madison Square.

00:33:34.160 --> 00:33:35.620
You know who the Shriners
are, right?

00:33:35.620 --> 00:33:37.810
Those guys who wear those fezzes.

00:33:37.810 --> 00:33:40.610
And here's what Najeeb said.

00:33:40.610 --> 00:33:44.510
He wrote that "Red
fezzes were as perplexing

00:33:44.510 --> 00:33:46.540
to the Orientals on the platform."

00:33:46.540 --> 00:33:50.430
That is the Syrians, "As the
costumes of these were interesting

00:33:50.430 --> 00:33:53.460 position:56%
and novel to those whom they faced."

00:33:53.460 --> 00:33:58.390
And you can imagine the Syrian
troop looking at these 15,000 men

00:33:58.390 --> 00:34:02.700
with their fezzes applauding
them and they performed

00:34:02.700 --> 00:34:07.040
as howling Dervishes, the Syrians,
you can imagine howling Dervishes.

00:34:07.040 --> 00:34:09.790
Yeah, it's quite marvelous.

00:34:09.790 --> 00:34:11.550
And Najeeb was ubiquitous.

00:34:11.550 --> 00:34:13.790
He was always giving interviews.

00:34:13.790 --> 00:34:16.960
He was friends with the
editors of The Herald Tribune.

00:34:16.960 --> 00:34:20.060
He was friends with the
New York World editors

00:34:20.060 --> 00:34:23.610
and he was always being interviewed
anytime anyone had a question

00:34:23.610 --> 00:34:27.700
about the New York Syrian
colony he was the one they asked

00:34:27.700 --> 00:34:29.000
for an opinion.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:32.240
He was ready to opine about
anything, but that picture

00:34:32.240 --> 00:34:34.060
that I show you is the only one.

00:34:34.060 --> 00:34:35.880
That was his memorial card.

00:34:35.880 --> 00:34:38.450
It's the only one that
I've ever seen of him.

00:34:38.450 --> 00:34:41.510
He suffered a stroke in 1900.

00:34:41.510 --> 00:34:47.370 position:56%
He had to give up both the newspaper
and his job at Ellis Island.

00:34:47.370 --> 00:34:51.180
And he decided to go back
to his original career,

00:34:51.180 --> 00:34:54.470
which was being a lawyer, which
he had studied in Maryville.

00:34:54.470 --> 00:34:58.460
And so he passed the New York
bar with no problem whatsoever.

00:34:58.460 --> 00:35:01.920
And on his way to the office,
they say the first day on his way

00:35:01.920 --> 00:35:07.840
to the office he suffered a second
stroke and he died in Manhattan.

00:35:07.840 --> 00:35:09.900
He was 43 years old.

00:35:09.900 --> 00:35:13.460
The newspaper already under new
management folded a few years

00:35:13.460 --> 00:35:15.370
after that out.

00:35:15.370 --> 00:35:19.890
He died without a will
and his widow claimed

00:35:19.890 --> 00:35:24.290
that his estate was
worth less than $200.

00:35:24.290 --> 00:35:28.770
He left a widow and six
children under the age of eleven.

00:35:28.770 --> 00:35:32.630
One of whom was born seven
months after he died.

00:35:32.630 --> 00:35:37.800
So. And his widow went to work
as a matron in Ellis Island,

00:35:37.800 --> 00:35:40.420
essentially took his
place at Ellis Island,

00:35:40.420 --> 00:35:41.720
but not really as an interpreter.

00:35:41.720 --> 00:35:43.560
She only could deal with the women

00:35:43.560 --> 00:35:47.800
and raised her six
children by herself.

00:35:50.230 --> 00:35:55.030
Abraham, although the
eldest, lived the longest.

00:35:55.030 --> 00:35:59.800
He was the most restless
of the Arbeelys'.

00:35:59.800 --> 00:36:04.660
He lived in practice in Austin,
Texas, Hot Springs, Arkansas,

00:36:04.660 --> 00:36:08.330
Washington DC, Los
Angeles, New York,

00:36:08.330 --> 00:36:12.070
Cairo and ended his days
in Washington DC again.

00:36:12.070 --> 00:36:14.740
He bought and sold real
estate in Los Angeles.

00:36:14.740 --> 00:36:19.990
He was really early pioneer real
estate speculator in Los Angeles

00:36:19.990 --> 00:36:24.630
because his wife's family were
pioneer Los Angeles families

00:36:24.630 --> 00:36:26.730
and they were big and
wealthy ranchers

00:36:26.730 --> 00:36:29.960
in Los Angeles in the
1860s and 1870s.

00:36:29.960 --> 00:36:33.240
He and his wife came in the 1880s
who set up a medical practice

00:36:33.240 --> 00:36:36.770
and he did real estate
speculation, did extremely well.

00:36:36.770 --> 00:36:40.560
He wrote a gigantic
Arabic English primer,

00:36:40.560 --> 00:36:44.970
which when put together
was 850 pages.

00:36:44.970 --> 00:36:48.780 position:56%
He sold it and [inaudible] through
subscription, through the newspaper,

00:36:48.780 --> 00:36:50.080
through Calcutta of America.

00:36:50.080 --> 00:36:52.410 position:56%
And it went through three printings.

00:36:52.410 --> 00:36:54.910
And you can still buy it.

00:36:54.910 --> 00:36:57.320
You can buy it on A Books.

00:36:57.320 --> 00:37:00.970
There are a couple of
copies available on A Books.

00:37:00.970 --> 00:37:04.950
He sold antiquities to
the Smithsonian Museum.

00:37:04.950 --> 00:37:10.420
He continued to write
albeit articles

00:37:10.420 --> 00:37:14.710
for various Arabic newspapers
until his death in 1919.

00:37:14.710 --> 00:37:19.100
He was the only member of the
family to live his full threescore

00:37:19.100 --> 00:37:23.420
and ten years and he had
outlived all of his brothers,

00:37:23.420 --> 00:37:27.070
and of course his parents.

00:37:27.070 --> 00:37:31.580
The dilemmas that beset other
immigrants about assimilation,

00:37:31.580 --> 00:37:37.140
success, honor, culture and raising
children in a Strange Land seemed

00:37:37.140 --> 00:37:39.740
to have skipped the Arbeelys'.

00:37:39.740 --> 00:37:42.610
For one thing they had always
planned to stay in America

00:37:42.610 --> 00:37:46.530
and they did their utmost
to take advantage of all

00:37:46.530 --> 00:37:47.830
that America had to offer.

00:37:47.830 --> 00:37:51.610
On the first day that Yosef and the
family arrived in New York he said

00:37:51.610 --> 00:37:54.710
"I want my children educated here
and I want them to marry here."

00:37:54.710 --> 00:37:59.580
Three of the sons were educated in
the United States and three married

00:37:59.580 --> 00:38:03.060
and had families in America,
just as their father had wished.

00:38:03.060 --> 00:38:07.370
Two of them married to what
the Syrians call Americans,

00:38:07.370 --> 00:38:08.670
although they weren't really.

00:38:08.670 --> 00:38:09.970
They were just non-Syrians

00:38:09.970 --> 00:38:13.890 position:56%
and the third one Felala married his
cousin Jimelee who came with them.

00:38:13.890 --> 00:38:19.130
But all of their children, so the
six of Najeeb, the five of Abraham

00:38:19.130 --> 00:38:22.280
and the two of Felala
all married Americans.

00:38:22.280 --> 00:38:27.560
Not one of them married another
Syrian or another Arab of any kind.

00:38:27.560 --> 00:38:30.850
More importantly from my
point of view as, you know,

00:38:30.850 --> 00:38:34.890
as a 19th ethnography,
they paved the way

00:38:34.890 --> 00:38:40.130
for what became a very respectable
way of making a living for all

00:38:40.130 --> 00:38:44.330
of the Syrians, which was
entertaining on the stage

00:38:44.330 --> 00:38:49.430
and in church halls and in YMCAs,
all over the United States,

00:38:49.430 --> 00:38:51.980
giving lectures, dressing
up as Muslims,

00:38:51.980 --> 00:38:55.550
doing reenactment of
Muslim weddings.

00:38:55.550 --> 00:38:57.980
And they made it respectable.

00:38:57.980 --> 00:39:03.730
Vaudeville for other peoples had
a kind of unsavory reputation,

00:39:03.730 --> 00:39:07.150
but for the Syrians it was no
different than running a store

00:39:07.150 --> 00:39:11.750
or being a paddler or having a
warehouse or a wholesale business

00:39:11.750 --> 00:39:17.020
and the Arbeelys' constructed
this life of entertaining

00:39:17.020 --> 00:39:21.280
and re-enacting Middle
Eastern rites and rituals

00:39:21.280 --> 00:39:25.200
and made it okay for everyone else.

00:39:25.200 --> 00:39:28.830
They seem to have constructed
and deftly manage the two halves

00:39:28.830 --> 00:39:32.250
of their identity, the
American and the other,

00:39:32.250 --> 00:39:36.490
succeeding in both worlds while
keeping them completely separate.

00:39:36.490 --> 00:39:41.870
If one can detect cracks in their
smooth presentation of self,

00:39:41.870 --> 00:39:45.590
they're perhaps to be found in
their restlessness and effort

00:39:45.590 --> 00:39:49.230
to find a place where they
might really fit, perhaps,

00:39:49.230 --> 00:39:52.520
in the return of two of the
brothers to the Middle East but not

00:39:52.520 --> 00:39:55.140 position:56%
to Damascus or Beirut, but to Cairo.

00:39:55.140 --> 00:39:59.240
And in the illnesses
which plague the family

00:39:59.240 --> 00:40:02.050
and cause the premature death
of five of the six brothers.

00:40:02.050 --> 00:40:06.370
And that they ended up
living and dying so far

00:40:06.370 --> 00:40:12.540
from each other may
indicate family strife.

00:40:12.540 --> 00:40:16.350
So being first was a
double edged sword.

00:40:16.350 --> 00:40:20.630 position:56%
They were able to forge their own
identity with few to criticize them,

00:40:20.630 --> 00:40:24.820
no role models and they
were truly on their own.

00:40:24.820 --> 00:40:28.270
And they made it up
as they went along.

00:40:28.270 --> 00:40:30.130
Not just because in the first years

00:40:30.130 --> 00:40:33.740
of their sojourn there were no
other Syrians in the United States

00:40:33.740 --> 00:40:38.490
for them to be with, but the
fact that they, as a family,

00:40:38.490 --> 00:40:43.900
seemed to live far away from other
Syrians even when Syrians came.

00:40:43.900 --> 00:40:45.700
The - you can see that Najeeb set

00:40:45.700 --> 00:40:49.080
up the business six blocks
from the Syrian colony.

00:40:49.080 --> 00:40:52.340
It doesn't sound a lot today
but in those days it was a lot.

00:40:52.340 --> 00:40:55.760
It meant that they were separated
and then you had people in DC,

00:40:55.760 --> 00:40:59.290
you had people in Los Angeles,
you had people in Atlanta, Georgia

00:40:59.290 --> 00:41:02.930 position:56%
and two men who went back to Cairo,
two brothers who went back to Cairo.

00:41:02.930 --> 00:41:06.710
So they really didn't
seem to be much part

00:41:06.710 --> 00:41:10.050
of the Syrian colony even
though they published the Syrian

00:41:10.050 --> 00:41:12.360
Colony Newspaper.

00:41:12.360 --> 00:41:15.550
Whatever their difficulties
may have been the Arbeelys',

00:41:15.550 --> 00:41:17.880
it must be said succeeded.

00:41:17.880 --> 00:41:22.340
Not financially because none
was ever rich, but in figuring

00:41:22.340 --> 00:41:27.240
out how an Arab might successfully
assimilate while keeping hold

00:41:27.240 --> 00:41:30.890
of his albeit Orientalized culture.

00:41:30.890 --> 00:41:32.570
We owe them a great deal.

00:41:32.570 --> 00:41:34.370
Thank you.

