00:47:41.610 --> 00:47:49.600
Do we have any documents about this
steady influx of Syrians or Arabs?

00:47:49.600 --> 00:47:50.900
&gt;&gt; Joan Weeks: Oh yeah.

00:47:50.900 --> 00:47:52.580
Oh yes. I mean that's
really what my book is

00:47:52.580 --> 00:47:54.410
about for the first 20 years.

00:47:54.410 --> 00:47:56.910
I mean, yes there's all
sorts of documentation.

00:47:56.910 --> 00:48:00.950
As you all probably know the
1890 census does not exist.

00:48:00.950 --> 00:48:02.250
It burned in a fire.

00:48:02.250 --> 00:48:06.140
The federal census, and
so that is the - for us,

00:48:06.140 --> 00:48:09.880
for the Syrians it would
have been a crucial census,

00:48:09.880 --> 00:48:12.030
because that would have
been the biggest influx.

00:48:12.030 --> 00:48:15.690
1880 census has a few people on it,

00:48:15.690 --> 00:48:21.110
but the 1890 census would have
been the key census for us.

00:48:21.110 --> 00:48:22.710
And it does not exist.

00:48:22.710 --> 00:48:28.180
So it's a big lack in our
knowledge of the influx of Syrians,

00:48:28.180 --> 00:48:32.110
but there are summary
reports of the 1890 census.

00:48:32.110 --> 00:48:34.740
So you can get a sense of
the, at least the numbers.

00:48:34.740 --> 00:48:39.020 position:56%
They came in the 1880s in a trickle.

00:48:39.020 --> 00:48:44.630 position:56%
In the 1890s, especially with the
Chicago fair caused this huge influx

00:48:44.630 --> 00:48:51.390
and HH Jessup, who's a Presbyterian
minister in Lebanon from the 1860s

00:48:51.390 --> 00:48:58.230
on laments the fact that the
town of Saali lost 300 young men

00:48:58.230 --> 00:49:03.580
in one week, all of whom were
coming to the Chicago fair.

00:49:03.580 --> 00:49:06.160
And that was probably a third

00:49:06.160 --> 00:49:08.990
of the male population
of Saali at that time.

00:49:08.990 --> 00:49:14.750
So it was a huge attraction for
people to come to the Chicago Fair

00:49:14.750 --> 00:49:18.120
in 1893 and a lot of
those people stayed.

00:49:18.120 --> 00:49:19.420
They stayed.

00:49:19.420 --> 00:49:23.040
So that was the biggest
pull to come.

00:49:23.040 --> 00:49:24.340
Yeah.

00:49:24.340 --> 00:49:30.120 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Man: You use the word Syrian
Diaspora, can you elaborate on that?

00:49:30.120 --> 00:49:33.980
&gt;&gt; Muhannad Salhi: You use
the word Syrian Diaspora.

00:49:33.980 --> 00:49:35.880
Can you elaborate on that?

00:49:35.880 --> 00:49:37.180
&gt;&gt; Joan Weeks: Yeah.

00:49:37.180 --> 00:49:39.470
So the Syrians didn't just
come to the United States.

00:49:39.470 --> 00:49:41.820
Of course they went everywhere.

00:49:41.820 --> 00:49:45.360
There are many, many, many Syrians
in South America, in Brazil,

00:49:45.360 --> 00:49:47.090
as you know because
some of the presidents

00:49:47.090 --> 00:49:50.400
of these countries have
Syrian names, right?

00:49:50.400 --> 00:49:53.680
They came to South America.

00:49:53.680 --> 00:49:57.440
There was lots of business going
on in Mexico, in Mexico City

00:49:57.440 --> 00:50:01.040
and in the Yucatan and [inaudible].

00:50:01.040 --> 00:50:05.740 position:56%
In the Caribbean, there was a big
Syrian colony in Cuba, one in Haiti,

00:50:05.740 --> 00:50:11.760
one in Jamaica, one in the
Dominican Republic and of course

00:50:11.760 --> 00:50:14.810
in all the states of the
Union, all the territories.

00:50:14.810 --> 00:50:22.500 position:56%
I have evidence of Syrians in Hawaii
in 1905 buying and selling property.

00:50:22.500 --> 00:50:25.340
And then, you know, of course
there were Syrians in Manchester,

00:50:25.340 --> 00:50:28.620
England starting in the 1860s.

00:50:28.620 --> 00:50:31.190
In France, the Maronites were going

00:50:31.190 --> 00:50:35.270
to France early this
year and West Africa.

00:50:35.270 --> 00:50:36.570
They were everywhere.

00:50:36.570 --> 00:50:37.870
&gt;&gt; Man: Why did they leave?

00:50:37.870 --> 00:50:40.310
&gt;&gt; Muhannad Salhi:
Why did they leave?

00:50:40.310 --> 00:50:41.610
&gt;&gt; Joan Weeks: Good question.

00:50:41.610 --> 00:50:43.760
So everyone debates this

00:50:43.760 --> 00:50:47.150
and the Syrians have their
own story about why they left.

00:50:47.150 --> 00:50:50.030
The Syrians always told the
same story, which I just love

00:50:50.030 --> 00:50:53.710
because it's the same story
that Yosef Arbeely told

00:50:53.710 --> 00:50:56.090
on the first day he got there.

00:50:56.090 --> 00:51:00.380
"Oh. we were oppressed by the
Muslim overlords and we came

00:51:00.380 --> 00:51:02.590
to bask in American freedom."

00:51:02.590 --> 00:51:05.970
Well, maybe, but probably not.

00:51:05.970 --> 00:51:08.700
Probably they came because
there was an opportunity

00:51:08.700 --> 00:51:10.000
and that's what Yosef saw.

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:16.580
He saw - he called it gold fever
and people came, the silk industry

00:51:16.580 --> 00:51:21.700
in Mount Lebanon collapsed
in the 1880s.

00:51:21.700 --> 00:51:26.120
That had - and they had converted
all of their farms to silkworms,

00:51:26.120 --> 00:51:29.610
so they were no longer
growing food for themselves.

00:51:29.610 --> 00:51:33.050
So they had silkworms, the
silk industry collapsed

00:51:33.050 --> 00:51:37.290
and they had no income.

00:51:37.290 --> 00:51:40.320 position:56%
So it got really, really hard for
them and there was - there were lots

00:51:40.320 --> 00:51:44.880
of famines going on in Mount
Lebanon in the 1880s and 1890s.

00:51:44.880 --> 00:51:47.100
And there was this
country beckoning.

00:51:47.100 --> 00:51:48.400
There were no visas.

00:51:48.400 --> 00:51:49.700
So people came.

00:51:49.700 --> 00:51:53.840
&gt;&gt; Man: Did a lot of them leave
because of the Ottoman draft?

00:51:53.840 --> 00:51:57.280 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Muhannad Salhi: Did a lot of them
leave because of the Ottoman draft?

00:51:57.280 --> 00:51:58.580
&gt;&gt; Joan Weeks: That was later.

00:51:58.580 --> 00:51:59.970
Yeah, that was in 1909.

00:51:59.970 --> 00:52:01.270
It was later.

00:52:01.270 --> 00:52:03.420
Yeah. Some certainly did.

00:52:03.420 --> 00:52:04.870
Some certainly did.

00:52:04.870 --> 00:52:11.600
But the big influx was
really from 1890 to 1910.

00:52:11.600 --> 00:52:13.430
And the people stayed
until the First World War.

00:52:13.430 --> 00:52:19.050 position:56%
So there were, you know, by about
1911 there were 9,000 Syrians coming

00:52:19.050 --> 00:52:21.410
every year to New York.

00:52:21.410 --> 00:52:23.160
So - to the United
States I should say,

00:52:23.160 --> 00:52:25.360
most of the landing in New York.

00:52:25.360 --> 00:52:27.210
And some of that has
to do with the draft.

00:52:27.210 --> 00:52:31.290
My grandfather - my grandmother
and grandfather went back to Syria

00:52:31.290 --> 00:52:36.380
to visit in 1914 and my
grandfather made a run

00:52:36.380 --> 00:52:42.010
for the American consulate in
Beirut to prove, to get a letter

00:52:42.010 --> 00:52:45.320
from the American consul that
he was an American citizen,

00:52:45.320 --> 00:52:46.750
so he would not be drafted.

00:52:46.750 --> 00:52:50.450
Because the Ottoman still
considered him an ottoman citizen

00:52:50.450 --> 00:52:53.790
and he wanted the consul to
say, essentially will fight

00:52:53.790 --> 00:52:56.220
for you if you get drafted.

00:52:56.220 --> 00:53:03.650
Yeah. So. Okay well thank you.

